1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:00,572
jump in.

2
00:00:01,252 --> 00:00:07,579
So they basically make a point of saying that machine learning doesn't happen in just one thing.

3
00:00:07,639 --> 00:00:10,982
It's not like sklearn.fit anymore.

4
00:00:11,423 --> 00:00:12,984
It is more of a pipeline.

5
00:00:13,725 --> 00:00:15,107
So what do we mean by this?

6
00:00:15,627 --> 00:00:25,077
If you have, if you think of something like you want to train an ImageNet model, what you want to do is you have like your data set somewhere.

7
00:00:25,057 --> 00:00:30,965
And that could be on in a database, it could be in the network somewhere.

8
00:00:31,285 --> 00:00:38,575
So if you have even something larger than ImageNet, you'll probably store it on a central server on an Amazon bucket somewhere.

9
00:00:38,615 --> 00:00:40,217
So this is in AWS.

10
00:00:40,878 --> 00:00:44,723
And the first thing you actually need to do is you need to read that data set.

11
00:00:45,203 --> 00:00:51,992
Now, usually you're not going to have enough memory on a machine to just load in the entire data set into memory.

12
00:00:51,972 --> 00:00:55,616
So that means this process here is streaming.

13
00:00:57,398 --> 00:00:59,660
So this is continuously streaming data points.

14
00:00:59,700 --> 00:01:04,466
And once you have used the data point, you're going to throw it away because you need space for the next one.

15
00:01:05,427 --> 00:01:08,470
And so the streaming is done continuously.

16
00:01:09,111 --> 00:01:11,674
The next process is read and decode.

17
00:01:12,054 --> 00:01:21,304
That means you have to read it from the network and actually bring it into a format where you can use it, usually something like an umpire array or a TensorFlow tensor.

18
00:01:21,284 --> 00:01:30,981
You need to apply some shuffling because usually you can't really trust the order that it is stored in.

19
00:01:31,181 --> 00:01:35,409
Often times there is a bias in the ordering, so you need some sort of a shuffle buffer here.

20
00:01:37,092 --> 00:01:40,298
Then often you want to apply some data augmentation to it.

21
00:01:40,718 --> 00:01:43,984
That means that you have one image.

22
00:01:43,964 --> 00:01:55,445
And we know for these models, if this is your cat, we know for these models that what can help is to basically make many, many different images from one image.

23
00:01:55,846 --> 00:02:04,922
So this could be by cropping part of it and saying, well, if it was a cat before the small upper right part here is still a cat.

24
00:02:04,942 --> 00:02:08,048
So this is one date, it's called data augmentation.

25
00:02:08,028 --> 00:02:10,912
and you're gonna apply a whole bunch of these things.

26
00:02:10,932 --> 00:02:14,857
So you can crop, you can rotate the image a bit, it's still a cat, right?

27
00:02:15,158 --> 00:02:24,190
And you can also change its luminance and a bit of its colors, you can jitter the colors, you can horizontally flip it and it'll still be a cat.

28
00:02:24,691 --> 00:02:28,416
And that's basically how you make many data points from one data point.

29
00:02:28,676 --> 00:02:29,918
And we know that helps.

30
00:02:29,898 --> 00:02:34,064
Then what you want to do is you want to batch this data.

31
00:02:34,084 --> 00:02:35,947
So you want to put it into mini batches.

32
00:02:37,288 --> 00:02:49,105
Since you've shuffled here, that means when the next time the same data point comes along, it's going to be batched with a different group of images and of course augmented differently.

33
00:02:49,085 --> 00:02:55,175
with a different group of images and that basically means it's a different training batch for the model.

34
00:02:55,375 --> 00:03:06,152
So this entire pipeline is basically a way that we take data points that we have and we make a whole bunch of variations and various groupings and batchings of it.

35
00:03:06,432 --> 00:03:12,021
And we know that helps enormously with the generalization capability of your final models.

36
00:03:12,001 --> 00:03:15,847
And then here you do your apply your SGD update.

37
00:03:15,868 --> 00:03:26,105
So that's usually where you forward propagate your data through your network, which here is F, you'll get like some Y hat as an output.

38
00:03:26,566 --> 00:03:30,432
And then you have your labels that also come through the pipeline.

39
00:03:30,412 --> 00:03:37,565
And you have some sort of loss function L that takes both as an input and gives you an output.

40
00:03:38,166 --> 00:03:40,590
And then you do your back propagation.

41
00:03:40,710 --> 00:03:48,825
So the back propagation would go through your loss function through your network and update the network parameters.

42
00:03:48,805 --> 00:03:51,409
search that your network learned something.

43
00:03:52,951 --> 00:03:58,018
Now this step to the right here is usually what we focus on when we do deep learning.

44
00:03:59,921 --> 00:04:11,758
The step on the right here, all of this, this can be done on a GPU or is usually done on something like a GPU or a TPU.

45
00:04:13,156 --> 00:04:18,226
But these things are getting faster and faster.

46
00:04:18,267 --> 00:04:23,036
The point the paper makes is that the TPUs and GPUs of the world are getting faster.

47
00:04:24,058 --> 00:04:29,229
But this entire other thing right here, this is basically CPU land.

48
00:04:29,530 --> 00:04:34,540
Now, I know there is some data augmentation now happening on the GPU and so on.

49
00:04:34,520 --> 00:04:42,672
But in essence, you can think of a pipeline where the thing to the left is happening on CPU and the thing to the right is happening on TPU.

50
00:04:43,073 --> 00:04:50,865
And even worse, let's say, the speed is continuously increasing.

51
00:04:51,125 --> 00:04:58,857
So in your pipeline, the kind of speed would be... So here is the network reading.

52
00:05:00,490 --> 00:05:06,136
And here over here is the GPU SGD step.

53
00:05:06,156 --> 00:05:07,197
And this is speed.

54
00:05:08,378 --> 00:05:16,746
Basically, the further to the right in your pipeline you go, the faster your hardware gets.

55
00:05:17,487 --> 00:05:23,373
And that means that if this is a continuous pipeline, right?

56
00:05:23,793 --> 00:05:27,797
That basically means that if I input something here,

57
00:05:27,777 --> 00:05:29,359
It goes through the pipeline.

58
00:05:29,399 --> 00:05:35,187
And even if this is all running in parallel, this thing over here is going to idle.

59
00:05:36,288 --> 00:05:41,215
Since this is the fastest part of the pipeline, it is going to just idle a lot.

60
00:05:43,678 --> 00:05:47,203
Because it can only consume things as fast as this thing can produce.

61
00:05:47,183 --> 00:05:57,198
Now, if you have some sort of a multi GPU machine and just train ImageNet, like you just run the code, usually, this is not the bottleneck.

62
00:05:57,318 --> 00:06:01,544
Usually, your GPUs here are at 100% capacity.

63
00:06:01,985 --> 00:06:03,367
So this paper is not for you.

64
00:06:03,907 --> 00:06:11,959
But if you are, let's say, a big company, have this network storage, have a big data set, have very expensive data augmentation,

65
00:06:11,939 --> 00:06:15,852
This happens, for example, this can happen in NLP and so on.

66
00:06:16,916 --> 00:06:25,003
This can be quite your situation where the earlier in the pipeline, the slower it is.

